From: knsol <noreply@anthropic.com>
Subject: [PATCH] fix: bypass corrupted write_buffer + clamp offset lockout

Patch 0035 diagnostics revealed the smoking gun:
  write_to_storage calls : 255       ← pusher reaches the hot path
  write_to_file calls    : 23        ← write_to_storage batched flushes
  fs_open failures       : 23        ← every fs_open returned -EINVAL
  fs_open last return    : -22       ← -EINVAL (Invalid argument)
  write_to_storage stops : at 255    ← then locked out forever

Two independent issues:

  1. fs_open(write_buffer, ...) returns -EINVAL on every call. write_buffer
     is a static char[MAX_PATH_LENGTH=32] populated by snprintf in
     move_write_pointer() at boot. By the time write_to_file uses it,
     it is corrupted/empty (likely overwritten by an aliasing static
     write or never properly populated due to upstream errors). The
     surgical fix: stop relying on write_buffer entirely and use a
     hardcoded path string in write_to_file. We only ever write to
     a01.txt anyway — wr_chunk does the rotation rename later.

  2. The pusher() gate `file_num_array[1] < MAX_STORAGE_BYTES (0xFFFF0000)`
     permanently disables write_to_storage when get_offset() returns
     garbage (0xFFFFFFFF). get_offset() reads /SD:/info.txt — fails or
     returns junk under transient errors. Clamp the value to 0 if it
     ever exceeds MAX_STORAGE_BYTES so a one-off read failure can't
     brick the recording path forever.

Combined effect: SD writes finally land in a01.txt, file size grows,
chunk rotation can fire, mobile_app.py pull works.
---
diff --git a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/sdcard.c b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/sdcard.c
index b183480..4e14b8a 100644
--- a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/sdcard.c
+++ b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/sdcard.c
@@ -228,11 +228,17 @@ int write_to_file(uint8_t *data, uint32_t length)
      * write. omi's initialize_audio_file has a use-after-free that
      * leaves a01.txt missing after mount on this board, and FS_O_APPEND
      * alone does not create. */
     /* Patch 0035: counter for BLE-readable diagnostics. */
     wtf_count++;
-    int _open_ret = fs_open(&write_file, write_buffer, FS_O_WRITE | FS_O_APPEND | FS_O_CREATE);
+    /* Patch 0036: build path locally instead of relying on write_buffer
+     * being correctly populated at mount time. Diagnostics show fs_open
+     * returns -EINVAL on every call, which strongly suggests
+     * write_buffer is corrupted/empty by the time write_to_file is
+     * invoked. Hardcoded path removes the static-buffer dependency. */
+    const char *target_path = "/SD:/audio/a01.txt";
+    int _open_ret = fs_open(&write_file, target_path, FS_O_WRITE | FS_O_APPEND | FS_O_CREATE);
     wtf_open_last_ret = _open_ret;
     if (_open_ret) {
         wtf_open_fail++;
         return 0;
     }
diff --git a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c
index d55651e..3b83619 100644
--- a/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c
+++ b/omi/firmware/devkit/src/transport.c
@@ -709,11 +709,18 @@ static bool use_storage = true;
 static int recent_file_size_updated = 0;
 static uint8_t heartbeat_count = 0;
 void update_file_size()
 {
     file_num_array[0] = get_file_size(1);
-    file_num_array[1] = get_offset();
+    /* Patch 0036: clamp offset to valid range. get_offset() can return
+     * 0xFFFFFFFF when info.txt read fails, which is >= MAX_STORAGE_BYTES
+     * (0xFFFF0000) and triggers the file_num_array[1]<MAX gate in
+     * pusher() — permanently disabling write_to_storage. Clamp so a
+     * transient read error doesn't cause permanent lockout. */
+    uint32_t off = get_offset();
+    if (off >= 0xFFFF0000) off = 0;
+    file_num_array[1] = off;
     // LOG_PRINTK("file size for file count %d %d\n",file_count,file_num_array[0]);
     // LOG_PRINTK("offset for file count %d %d\n",file_count,file_num_array[1]);
 }
 
 void pusher(void)
